For the **base-case** NPV, we can solve it using this formula:

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{NPV}&=-\text{Initial cost}+\text{OCF} \times \text{Annuity factor}
\end{aligned}$$

**b.** The sensitivity of the NPV to the changes in fixed cost can be solved using this formula:

$$\begin{aligned}
\dfrac{\Delta \text{NPV}}{\Delta \text{FC}}
\end{aligned}$$

This generally shows how much the NPV will change if the fixed cost is increased by a dollar.

**c.** We can recall that the cash break-even point is the point wherein the company has exactly zero operating cashflow. This can be solved using this formula:

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Q}&=\dfrac{\text{FC}}{\text{P}-\text{v}}
\end{aligned}$$

**d.** We can recall that the accounting break-even occurs when the revenue is exactly zero. This can be solved using the formula:

$$\begin{aligned}
Q&=\dfrac{FC+D}{P-v}
\end{aligned}$$

The degree of operating leverage measures the effect of the change in quantity to the revenue of the company. This can be solved using:

$$\begin{aligned}
DOL&=1+\dfrac{FC}{OCF}
\end{aligned}$$
